      "I usually don't write anything about books I don't finish, but now I have to.<br/><br/>First of all, this book is 20 years old and I don't feel we progressed too much as a society when it comes to rape. It's extremely important to talk about it and to educate people. Because guess what, this is much more common that most people realise. According to NSVRC, 1 of 5 (!) women will be raped during their lives at some point and this is very alarming. Yet, this subject is still taboo and victims are often blamed. <br/>Theme of this book is important and it should be discussed much more in YA literature. <br/><br/>This book had a potential to be a brilliant psychological masterpiece that offers viewpoint of a rape victim (if you want this, watch Netflix series Unbelievable). <br/>I might be quite old for high school stories, especially those dumb American ones that basically don't make any sense. But here I stopped around page 70 because I was so bored. About 70% of what I read was describing lectures she attended. Wtf, I'm not interested to know what you learn on biology each fucking week! <br/>So yeah, this just wasn't for me, this book didn't meet its amazing potential and it's written in quite a childish way so I'm not a target audience anymore.<br/>BUT <br/>I'm glad it was written and it's popular, because like I've said, we need to talk about this more.<br/><br/><br/>Also, here're 2 amazing songs telling story about rape:<br/>Yungblud - Polygraph eyes<br/>Sublime - Date rape <br/>Highly recommended.",
