    "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
    "My Review":
      "I have so many things to say about this that I don't know where to start. <br/><br/>Colleen Hoover might be the only author whose books I'm adding to my to-read list automatically. I don't even care what they are about, I just know I want to read them.<br/><br/>I went into this book completely blindly. I had absolutely no idea what is it about. Actually, I found out that this book is about infertility in Chapter 4. <br/><br/>I love this subject! Personally, I haven't heard of any other book about this subject. In fact, it's still a taboo, even in the modern society. But we need to talk about it more as that's something a lot of people struggle with. <br/><br/>It was quite fascinating to me. Being pregnant seems like one of the scariest things in the world to me, I don't think I'll get through it in the future. <br/>It was very interesting from psychological point of view as well as for me to see a character that was basically my exact opposite. And it was quite heartbreaking.<br/><br/>I felt really bad for Quinn for not being able to be the only thing she's ever wanter to be - a mother. However, she annoyed me so badly for the most of the book and actually made me mad that she's the reason why this book didn't get 5*. <br/><br/>My main issue? That complete lack of conversation between her and Graham! That bothered me so much. Ofc, that wasn't only her fault - however Graham kept fighting. He fought for their relationship, for their marriage, because he loved her too much. But both people need to want it.<br/><br/>He was the sweetest. I think, anyone would be the luckiest person alive to have a partner like him. Someone that loves you unconditionally like he did. That was the most painful part of that book for me - to see how much he loves her and how she doesn't appreciate it - while finding someone like that is incredibly rare.<br/><br/>There was a part that almost made me cry. In the bus full of people, so I had to stop reading. So it's safe to say this book made me feel a whole range of emotion. <br/><br/>And I absolutely loved that ending. <spoiler>Not just that puppy - I love how author wasn't afraid of the theme of childless woman - most authors would make her have a child at the end. But she not only made it more realistic this was, but she also shown that life without children can be also fulfilling and great. That's something people who can't or don't want to have children can appreciate.</spoiler><br/><br/>So well done, Colleen (again)! Need to read Too late, Regretting you and Heart bones soon",
